	<sect1 id="keymanager">
		<title>Encryption Key Manager</title>
		<para>
			The Encryption Key Manager (&app;) provides a front end to many of the 
			features of 
			<ulink url="http://www.gnupg.org" type="http">Gnu Privacy Guard (GPG)</ulink>.
			Several of the tasks able to be performed are explained below:
		</para>
		<sect2 id="generate">
			<title>Generate a Key Pair</title>
			<para>
				There are two methods of generating key pairs in &app;:the key
				 generation assistant and the advanced generation dialog.  
			</para>
			<para>
				 Access the assistant by choosing
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Key</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Create Key Pair</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				.  Select <guilabel>Assistant</guilabel> and press the enter key or
				 press <guibutton>Continue</guibutton>.
			</para>
			<para>
				Access the advanced generation dialog by choosing 
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Key</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Create Key Pair</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				.  Select <guilabel>Advanced</guilabel> and press the enter key or 
				press <guibutton>Continue</guibutton>.
			</para>
			<sect3 id="generate-assistant">
				<title>Key Generation Assistant</title>
				<para>
					After following the instructions above, the assistant will 
					walk you through the process of generating a key pair.
				</para>
			</sect3>
			<sect3 id="generate-adv">
				<title>Advanced Key Generation</title>
				<para>
					After following the instructions above, you will be 
					presented with a dialog to fill in.  The fields are detailed 
					below.
				</para>
				<variablelist>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Full Name</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								Enter your full name in the form
								<programlisting>&lt;first&gt; &lt;last&gt;</programlisting>
								A middle name or initial is optional.
								<note>You must enter at least 5 
								characters in this field.</note> 
							</para>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Email Address</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								Your email address is how most
								people will locate your key on a
								key server or other key provider.
								Make sure it is correct before
								continuing. 
								<note>It should be of the form 
								<programlisting>&lt;user name&gt;@&lt;domain name&gt;</programlisting></note>
							</para>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Key Comment</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								The comment field can be used to 
								place any additional information 
								into the displayed name of your new 
								key pair.  This information can be 
								searched for on key servers.
							</para>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Key Type</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								This field specifies the encryption 
								algorithms used to generate your keys.
							</para>
							<variablelist>
								<varlistentry>
									<term>DSA &amp; ElGamal</term>
									<listitem>
										<para>
										This is the suggested 
										choice as it will allow 
										you to encrypt/decrypt/
										sign/verify as needed
										</para>
									</listitem>
								</varlistentry>
								<varlistentry>
									<term>DSA</term>
									<listitem>
										<para>
										Will allow signing only.
										</para>
									</listitem>
								</varlistentry>
								<varlistentry>
									<term>RSA</term>
									<listitem>
										<para>
										Will allow signing only.
										</para>
									</listitem>
								</varlistentry>
							</variablelist>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Key Length</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								This is the length of the key in bits.  
								The longer the key, the more secure it 
								will be, provided a strong passphrase is
								used.  Conversely, performing any
								operation with a longer key will require 
								more time than it would with a shorter 
								key.  Acceptable values are between 1024 
								and 4096 bits.  At least 2048 bits is 
								recommended.
							</para>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Expiration Date</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								This is the date at which the key will 
								cease to be usable for performing 
								encryption or signing operations.  A 
								reasonable time to set it to is 6 
								months.  You will have to generate a new 
								key after this amount of time passes.  
								<note>Sign your new key with your old one 
								before it expires to preserve your trust 
								status.</note>
							</para>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
					<varlistentry>
						<term><guilabel>Passphrase</guilabel></term>
						<listitem>
							<para>
								Use similar practices to generating a 
								strong password when choosing a 
								passphrase.  The difference between a 
								password and a pass phrase is that in a 
								passphrase spaces are valid characters.
							</para>
						</listitem>
					</varlistentry>
				</variablelist>
			</sect3>
		</sect2>
		<sect2 id="import">
			<title>Import Keys</title>
			<para>
				Importing keys can be performed by choosing
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Key</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Import</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				and selecting a file containing at least one ASCII armored public key in 
				the file chooser.  You can also paste keys by selecting an ASCII armored 
				public block of text, copying it to the clipboard and choosing
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Edit</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Paste Keys</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				.
			</para>
		</sect2>
		<sect2 id="export">
			<title>Export Keys</title>
			<para>
				Exporting keys can be performed by selecting the keys in the main window 
				and choosing
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Key</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Export</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				and selecting a file containing at least one ASCII armored public key in 
				the file chooser.  You can also export keys to the clipboard, in an 
				ASCII armored block of text, by selecting the keys in the main window 
				and choosing
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Edit</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Copy Keys</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				.
			</para>
		</sect2>
		<sect2 id="backup">
			<title>Backup Keyrings</title>
			<para>
				You can back up your public and private keyrings to an archived file by 
				choosing
				<menuchoice>
					<guimenu>Key</guimenu>
					<guimenuitem>Backup Keyrings</guimenuitem>
				</menuchoice>
				.  Enter a file name with a valid archive extenision and specify the 
				location to save the archive.  
				<note>You can choose any of the archive types 
				<application>file-roller</application> supports.</note>
			</para>
		</sect2>
